<DOC><DOCNO> AP890203-0029 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-02-03-89 0306EST</FILEID><FIRST>r w PM-SenateConfirmations     02-03 0230</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Senate Confirmations,230</SECOND><HEAD>Senate Gives Unanimous Consent to Bush Nominations</HEAD><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Former Rep. Jack Kemp, retired congressmanManuel J. Lujan and two other high-level nominees were approved inthe most recent Senate votes on President Bush's appointments, withKemp becoming secretary of the Department of Housing and UrbanDevelopment and Lujan becoming secretary of the Interior.   Also confirmed Thursday were Michael J.Boskin, to be chairman ofthe Council of Economic Advisers, and William J. Reilly as head ofthe Environmental Protection Agency. The vote for each of thenominees was 100-0.   Kemp won unanimous approval by the Senate Banking Committeeearlier in the day and his nomination was sent quickly to the Senatefloor for final action.   His approval came after the former New York Republicancongressman agreed to give up more than $55,000 in speaking feesafter being told he had apparently violated federal limits onoutside income for members of Congress.   Lujan, 60, was a 20-year member of Congress from New Mexico untilhis retirement last year.   He was approved 19-0 by the Senate Energy and Natural ResourcesCommittee on Wednesday.   Reilly, former president of the World Wildlife Fund andConservation Foundation, was approved by the Senate Environment andPublic Works Committee on a 16-0 vote earlier in the day. He haspromised a ``new era'' at the EPA in strong enforcement ofenvironmental laws.</TEXT></DOC>